\section intro_sec Introduction

SPoCA stands for Spatial Possibilistic Classification Algorithm.

It is a multi-channel unsupervised spatially-constrained fuzzy clustering algorithm.

It's purpose is to segment Extreme Ultra Violet (EUV) images of the sun into 3 categories: Quiet Sun (QS), Active %Region (AR) and Coronal Hole (CH)

\section history_sec History

The software was first develloped by Vincent Barra in 2007.

It has been completely rewritten by Benjamin Mampaey starting in 2009, and has been in developpement since.

It received several improvements, with the help of Cis Verbeeck and Veronique Delouille.

\section references_sec References

- [1] Barra, V., Delouille, V., Hochedez, J.-F., & Chainais, P.:2005 `Segmentation of EIT Images Using Fuzzy Clustering: a Preliminary Study', ESA Special Publication, 600, 77.1.
- [2] Barra V., Delouille V., Hochedez J.-F.:2008 `Segmentation of extreme ultraviolet solar images via multichannel fuzzy clustering', Advances in Space Research, 42, 917--925.
- [3] Barra V., Delouille V., Kretzschmar M., Hochedez J.-F.:2009 `Fast and robust segmentation of solar EUV images: algorithm and results for solar cycle 23', A&A, 505(1), 2009, 361--371
- [4] V. Barra, V. Delouille, and J.-F. Hochedez: 2009 `Segmentation, Tracking and Characterization of Solar Features from EIT Solar Corona Images', Lecture Notes in Computer Science, Volume 5575/2009, 199--208,

*/

